This tutorial has been created to guide users through the steps to create and validate a dataset of road intersection images from major cities around the world. The aim is to create a program to find, create and validate traffic images from roadways intersections from major world cities like Bangkok, Mumbai, Accra, Bogota, etc.

For convenience, we'll be concentrating on one city - Bangkok for the purpose of this tutorial.

City Location Data¶

In order to get the images for the road intersections of the city, we need the coordinates of the same. For that purpose, we need to first obtain the coordinate data for the entire city, with enough resolution to include roadways. We do so by obtaining shapefiles for the city. Shapefiles are digital files used to store geographic data associated with particular geographic points. Following are the open source shapefile resource available online:

  • Geofabrik, updated daily (usually) with a global extract and some countries. Shapefiles with the following are provided: buildings, landuse, natural, places, point, railways, roads and waterways.
  • OpenStreetMapData.com. Coastline data only
  • Metro Extracts service
  • osm-x-tractor.org offers global and continental extracts. Shapefiles are generated for buildings, roads, landuse, places, POI, natural, hydrography and vegetation. Updated every two weeks.
  • osm2shp.ru here you can download openstreetmap data in shapefiles format. Data divided by regions: North and South America, Australia and Oceania, Africa, Europa and Asia.61 layers for download. Data filtered by "Map Features" conditions.
  • BBBike.org extract service offers shape files for more than 200 cities and regions worldwide, updated weekly. Separate shapefiles for points, places, waterways, roads, railways, landuse and buildings with relevant tags, then shapefiles with all points, lines and polygons together.

Shapefiles¶

For the purpose of this tutorial, we'll download the Bangkok shapefile from BBBike.org.
Go to Bangkok shapefile download. Search for Bangkok in the search bar and choose shapefile as the Format and you'll see a page like this:

You can also select an area by adding polygon points and download the shapefile for the selected area. The shapefile includes specific information on the type of roads at any specific point. A point with more than one road is classified as an intersection. We'll be using this point to get the intersection coordinates.

The shapefile includes specific information on the type of roads at any specific point. A point with more than one road is classified as an intersection. Lets first create a function to filter out roads with certain attributes (for e.g. tunnels).

In [3]:
def road_filter(road):        #use this function to remove certain type of characteristics; for e.g.
    if ('highway' in road['properties']
            and road['properties']['highway'] is not None
            and road['properties']['highway'] != 'path'
            and road['properties']['highway'] != 'footway'):
        return True
    if ('class' not in road['properties'] or road['properties']['class'] == 'highway'
            and road['properties']['bridge'] == 0
            and road['properties']['tunnel'] == 0):
        return True
    return False

We can pass the read roads shapefile to the roads_filter function now and pass the roads shapely geometries representing road segments to a list.

Now, lets create a function which calculates the intersection points of all roads. You can go to this Github repo from which I took the reference of this function. We are basically taking intersections of the shapely geometry (a Linestring in our case) which represents road segments. A road segment in our case is represented by a shapely linestring which is a collection of coordinates of the road segment. For an intersection to exist, it should be present, it should be present in at least 2 road Linestrings and hence we perform set intersection using itertools and shapely to get the coordinates of the intersections.

In [ ]:
def get_intersections(roads):
    intersections = []
    for road1, road2 in itertools.combinations(roads, 2):
        if road1.intersects(road2):
            intersection = road1.intersection(road2)
            if 'Point' == intersection.type:
                intersections.append(intersection)
            elif 'MultiPoint' == intersection.type:
                intersections.extend([pt for pt in intersection])
            elif 'MultiLineString' == intersection.type:
                multiLine = [line for line in intersection]
                first_coords = multiLine[0].coords[0]
                last_coords = multiLine[len(multiLine)-1].coords[1]
                intersections.append(Point(first_coords[0], first_coords[1]))
                intersections.append(Point(last_coords[0], last_coords[1]))
    return unary_union(intersections)  # The unary_union removes duplicate points

intersection = get_intersections(roads)
print("number of intersections: ",len(intersection))

Let's write a function which gets the panorama (360°) images of given cooridinates from Google StreetView. Many cities/places present in the StreetView database have multiple rounds of image collection i.e. images of the same place taken at different times. We can collect all these images as well as their image IDs to a create temporal trend for the indicator of interest.

In [ ]:
panorama_history = []

def panoid_history(coordinates, save=True, visual_save=False):
    """This function is for getting the panoids of panoramic views from Google Street View
    as a function of multiple years and  months"""
    for long,lat in coordinates:
        # print("lat:", lat)
        panoids = streetview.panoids(lat=lat, lon=long)
        panorama_history.append(panoids)

    if save:
        with open('panorama_hitorical_pickle', 'wb') as f:
            pickle.dump(panorama_history, f)

    if visual_save:
        with open('panorama_history.txt', 'w') as f:  # writing to a file - human readable
            for item in panorama_history:
                f.write("%s\n" % item)

# with open('panorama_hitorical_pickle', 'rb') as f:    #pickle load function

panoid_history(list_arrays, save=True, visual_save=True)

We can also create a function to download and save these panoids. The penoid_list is a list of panoid IDs represented above as panoid_history.
flat_dir is the address of the folder you want the images to be downloaded to, heading is the central heading angle and key is the Google API key.

(Get the API key by following these directions)

def save_penoid_images(penoid_list, heading, flat_dir, key):
    """function to download penoid images"""
    for penoid_ind in penoid_list:
        streetview.api_download(penoid_ind, heading, flat_dir, key)

def image_download(apiargs):
    # Get a list of all possible queries from multiple parameters
    api_list = google_streetview.helpers.api_list(apiargs)

    # Create a results object for all possible queries
    results = google_streetview.api.results(api_list)

    # # Preview results
    results.preview()

    # Download images to directory 'downloads'
    results.download_links(d)

    # Save metadata
    results.save_metadata('metadata.json')

All the above code is available in image_data_generation.py file.
